		 	<span id="comment_score_64570255" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64570255); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~ctilsie242">ctilsie242</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~ctilsie242">( 4841247 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64570255"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64570255"><p>e-Ink displays have been used by shops for ages, and before that, battery powered LCD price tags.  For example, one HEB location had all their prices on LED tags so they could just have someone run around with a scanner-like tool, that scanned the barcode, then transmitted an IR sequence to each tag to change the price.  It took a bit to hit every tag, but it saved time of physically switching tags.</p><p>I have seen Best Buys use e-Ink displays to change prices on stuff in real time.  Because the display is e-Ink<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64570255">

